The Brehon Laws are certainly a worthwhile subject of study &amp; I don't think
anyone has ever heard/read me say otherwise.  And individuals can attempt to
follow Brehon Laws if they *choose* to, either singly or in a group that has
made an agreement to that effect.  They do not, however, get to try to
*force* other people to and then ridicule and slander them when they refuse.
Some of us are content with the laws of the countries we're living in and
don't want to resort to some older system that supports things like slavery
&amp; a father having unaccountable power of life and death over his children.
Some of us aren't Irish &amp; don't consider the Brehon Laws as any part of our
heritage.  Some of us have no patience for the xtian or islamist fundies who
wander in here and try to proselytize &amp; are damned if we're gonna put up
with it just because someone calls themselves pagan.

There was never a Druid Religion with a pantheon and prayers/liturgies and
dogma and a hierarchy of clergy standing between &quot;the gods&quot; and everybody
else.  If people want to follow one of these recently-manufactured religions
inaccurately labeled &quot;Druid&quot;, that's their choice, but again--they don't get
to *force* other people to agree with them--or ridicule and slander them
when they refuse.

By all means keep all the old lore--but bear in mind that in being written
down it may have been distorted.  Learning about the mindset of the people
who did the writing will help in discerning where the distortions may occur.

Most of all keep the reverence for the Land and the devotion to living in
balance with Her.  Keep the connection to the Otherworld that every human
has been born with from the beginning of the species &amp; work to strengthen
it.  Keep remembering that everyone is ultimately responsible for their own
path.  Toss anything that gets in the way of this, especially hierarchies &amp;
dogmas &amp; self-styled authorities who demand you do things their way no
matter what.

Dana
