Hmm! Well, I'm not overly keen on the expression 'druid religion'. One
couldn't say that there was a single pagan Celtic religion; rather there was
a multiplicity of them, each one being the religion of their tribe. OK, one
might argue that these religions had something in common, in the same way
that their cultures had common elements by virtue of cultural contact
through trade (both short distance and long distance), clientship and so on.

Then again, one can say exactly the same thing about the Greeks - each
city-state had its own religion, although the Greeks had in idea of
Greekness (itself the result of the Persian Wars and the comparison between
their cultural similarities and the Other) and subscribed to a common
cosmological framework that revolved around a common set of gods and heroes,
plus a common set (relatively speaking) of cultural values. Aegean culture
seems to have emerged as a result of convergent evolution and acculturation
mediated by trade so that a common culture and language emerged *before*
there was a sense of 'Greekness' - the idea of 'Greekness' versus the
barbarian is absent from, for example, the Odyssey. It required the threat
of a culture that did not conform to 'Greek' cultural norms to crystallise
the idea of being Greek, and then only by opposition to the barbarian. That
was Athens' contribution. One might note that later Greeks used the idea of
'Greekness' to claim that some Greeks (them) were more Greek that other
Greeks (whoever they had a down on).

A similar mechanism - i.e. cultural similarities and a common language
developing through trade and other forms of contact - have been proposed for
meso-America and, interestingly, for the emergence of Germanic languages. In
the latter case it has been proposed that this developed from a trading
culture centred on the Baltic.In short, cultural similarity precedes an
overall ethnic identity, which may not develop until the culture bangs into
another unrelated culture and survives it. This doesn't mean that common or
similar institutions aren't in the process of developing - in the ancient
world religion and trade were intertwined, since the gods were taken as
witnesses to contracts. A certain degree of similarity is helpful in such
cases - then again, prolonged trade contact might well drive convergence in
this field.

Now you could argue that the 'Celts' were in the same position as the Greeks
were before the Persian wars. As I remarked in my dissertation, if the
Greeks hadn't taken up writing, we might now have Hellenosceptics arguing
that there were no such thing as 'Greeks'! :-) After all, you have a
multiplicity of city-state religions, different burial customs, no overall
centralised structure, and even the existence of Greeks for whom the polis
was not the natural basis of organisation. :-) How on earth could there be a
pan-Greek identity? :-)

There's plenty of mechanisms for acculturation between Celtic-speaking
peoples - including trade - over very long distances. You could therefore
argue with some justification that, over wide areas, individual tribal
religions would have elements in common. Some awareness of the cultural
similarities between themselves and the differences between them and the
Greeks and the Romans was probably there, though this does not mean that
there was a pan-Celtic identity nor does it mean that there was one Celtic
religion, anymore than there was one Greek religion. If you like, you could
say that there were many variations (but then there are those
Celtic-speaking cultures that were further away from Mediterranean
influences).

Of course, how the everyday person thought about religious ideas, and how
the druids thought about them are two entirely different things. One might
compare and contrast the perspectives of the average Hindu and the Brahmins.
Given the possibility of  common religious framework over wide areas,
chances are that druids from different tribes might have developed broadly
similar abstract ways of thinking about things - this does not however
constitute a druid religion, anymore than you can talk about a Brahmin
religion. In fact given that the notion of firenne gets in the way of
developing dogma (not to mention the love of ambiguity), it is difficult to
see how one could have one overall 'druid religion'. The Colloquy of the Two
Sages, by contrast, would suggest the possibility of many different
understandings of a common framework, but that's more like philosophy
(itself originally a religious pursuit) than religion.

Now OK, you might be able to use the term 'druid religion' as a shorthand
expression of a multiplicity of different abstract understandings based on a
common religious framework, or relatively common religious and cultural
frameworks. However, the term is also open to misunderstanding.

As for the Brehon laws. Hmm! Well, speaking logically, folks may chose to
follow them personally, but they are not part of a recognised modern legal
system and they are unenforceable if someone chooses not to follow them. Nor
would modern courts accept them as a defence if they led you to break the
established secular law. I can imagine the reaction of a court (and the
young lady) if someone claimed that they were now married to a woman by
virtue of abducting her. :-)

Though they are purely Irish, it is not unlikely that other Celtic speaking
areas had something similar. As I recall, the laws of Hywel Dda are a mix of
Late Roman law with indigenous law - there is some evidence of indigenous
law still operating under the Empire, the only requirement being that it
agreed in the important particulars with Imperial law. Perhaps that might be
a good model to follow. :-)

On the various specifics I've seen mentioned recently, I can't recall
anything, anywhere, from the law codes that says that an Irish druid can't
be satirised. Come to that, there's nothing to say that a file can't be
satirised either. In fact satire was a just response for the failure of a
party. To argue that no one from outside Ireland could satirise a druid or
file would be to argue that Irish druids and filidh were always in the
right - and the stories suggest otherwise. Whilst an outsider's honour price
might be lower - though not always, since they might be a client of a king,
or even the 'client' of a god (and you try paying the eric of a god!) - they
were still due their honour price if wronged. If that wasn't forthcoming,
satire might be an appropriate response. Mind you, the law codes were
largely concerned with matters internal to Ireland, so they don't discuss
the matter specifically - but the logic of the codes as a whole would lead
me to conclude that an Irish druid or file could indeed be satirised by
someone from outside Ireland under circumstances where the Irish person had
wronged the outsider.

Secondly, you're not allowed to be a bystander. In principal I agree with
this. However, neither should it be used to argue that all and sundry should
join in on one side or the other. When you just have several people shouting
at each other, you can pretty much presume that each party will consider
themselves wronged, and that you'll be getting a biased view from all
involved, no matter who is in the right. Of course in some cases, none of
them may be entirely in the right (or even in the right in any sense at
all), and each is worse than the other. :-) One might, for example,
postulate a situation where several robbers fell out over dividing the
spoils of their robbery, and each justifying the reasons why they betrayed
or attacked the other by saying that they were in the right.

If you are aware of the rights and wrongs of the matter then sure, make your
judgement and chose a course of action. If you're not - well, that's why you
have a brain. You head is for more than simply keeping your hat on. You find
out what facts you can and, taking into account things like culpability,
form a judgement. Having assessed the situation, you then decide what, if
anything, you should do about it.

Of course, there's the whole question of 'joining in'. If the whole venture
is ill-wished, then you'll be doing no good service by joining in. I'm
minded of a woman I knew once, years ago, who got beaten up by her then
boyfriend whilst he was drunk. She knew that he was somewhat impressed by
me - well, frightened might be nearer the mark - so she asked me to put the
frighteners on him to ensure that he didn't do it again. I refused. She
asked why. I pointed out that the fact that she'd asked me meant that she
was pretty sure that it was going to happen again. Sure, I could frighten
the guy whilst he was sober - he was not however a problem whilst sober. He
was, OTOH, likely to have the potential consequences slip his mind whilst
drunk, start on her, remember half way through, and then hit her harder so
that she didn't tell me. The whole notion was ill-wished. A better course of
action, since she was obviously sure he'd do it again, was to dump him and
find somewhere else to live. If she wanted to do that - well, there's the
couch. She could put up till she got
