Again, do you have an historical reference for that? By the 7th century the
filidh have become the sole inheritors of the rights and privileges of the
druids so they would have inherited that right as well. Druids, on the other
hand, disappear from law codes after the 8th or 9th century. Indeed one
could make a reasonable academic argument that the two groups were
essentially the same, that the process was one of evolution rather than
replacement, and that in fact the term 'druid' had changed by the 8th or 9th
century, as language always changes, to mean, more or less, sorcerer or
magician, rather than the far more complex role seen in earlier times.

As support for this, one might note that the law codes stipulate health care
for an 8th century druid based on relative status. Whilst this would have
meant a reduction in status for one of the elite to be what was meant by
'druid' in the 8th century, it would have been a step up in status for
someone below the rank of bo-aire. It would thus have been a suitable step
up in status for someone of a lower status to be known for their magic, and
thus as a druid. Or to put it another way, it would have been a reduction in
status for a file to break ranks and use magic that way, whilst it would
have been an increase in status for non-filidh to do so.

On balance, I'd suspect the law was largely to control what the filidh and
their students got up to, and not for the first time in Irish history. OTOH,
no one was too fussed about magical practitioners from the lower orders, as
long as their activities were covered by the codes, particularly by codes
concerning status. Issues of status were of big concern to ancient Irish
jurisprudence.

Consequently, whilst the members of the elite group known in former times as
druids (as well as poets and brehons) were evolving into the filidh, the
term 'druid' was coming to mean someone from a very different group who was
simply known for using magic, before effectively becoming obsolete
altogether prior to the later Revival druids. None of which is at all
surprising - Gildas uses the Latin 'magi' (sing. magus) to describe the
probable British equivalent of druids in the courts of 6th century kings
such as Maelgwn Gwynedd.

